{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473964"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:16:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:16:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11571"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11571"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.28,0.01,0.11,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4200"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"36113"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4200"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11571"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20912"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"10997"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7102"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44103"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"36113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/36113"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 17-year-old woman presents to her GP complaining of fatigue. She is on a balanced diet, has no previous medical problems and takes no medications. Menarche was at the age of 13 and she describes light menstrual bleeds lasting for three days each month. She states that her mother has a low haemoglobin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer physical examination is normal except for pale conjunctiva. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA complete blood count shows RBCs 6.06 x10\u003Csup\u003E^\u003C/sup\u003E12/L(3.8-5.8) , haemoglobin 100 g/L (119-160) MCV of 66 fl (80-100), and RDW 12% (10-15). The white blood cell count and platelets are normal. A peripheral smear shows microcytosis, hypochromia and occasional target cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anaemia of inflammation","Iron deficiency anaemia","Hypothyroidism","Sideroblastic anaemia","Thalassaemia trait"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most common cause of a microcytic anaemia is \u003Cstrong\u003Eiron deficiency,\u003C/strong\u003E but it is unlikely in this young patient who has a normal diet and no bleeding source. Furthermore, her family history points to an alternative cause. In this case, the greater degree of microcytosis for the level of anaemia (Mentzer index is \u0026lt; 13), normal RDW, and the presence of target cells, \u003Cem\u003Eall\u003C/em\u003E favour the diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Ethalassaemia trait\u003C/strong\u003E over iron deficiency. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EQuantitative HbA2 determination is the most valuable test for \u03b2-thalassaemia carrier detection, HbA2 expected to be \u0026gt;3.5 %)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypothyroidism,\u003C/strong\u003E an anaemia is usually macrocytic. In addition, characteristic clinical features (weight gain, constipation, cold intolerance) in addition to fatigue would be expected to be present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe MCV in \u003Cstrong\u003Eanaemia of inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E is usually normal or slightly reduced. These patients typically have a history of chronic infection or inflammation, cancer, or liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESideroblastic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E could be congenital or acquired (related to drugs, alcohol, or lead poisoning). RDW is usually high, and blood smear shows dimorphic red blood cells, moderate poikilocytosis, hypochromic teardrop, coarse basophilic stippling, and / or Pappenheimer bodies. Bone marrow staining will demonstrate ringed sideroblasts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Thalassaemia has greater degree of microcytosis for any level of anaemia than does iron deficiency.","RDW is normal or slightly elevated in thalassaemia trait and usually elevated in iron deficiency anaemia","Mentzer index (MI= MCV/RBCs) is \u003C 13 in thalassaemia trait, and \u003E 13 in iron deficiency"],"references":["Cappellini MD, Russo R, Andolfo I, Iolascon A. Inherited microcytic anemias. Hematology. 2020 Dec 4","Minervo F, Reis P, Ribeiro De Andrade R, Fernando C, Rodrigues S, Timb\u00f3 Barbosa F. Discriminant indexes to simplify the differential diagnosis between iron deficiency anemia and thalassemia minor in individuals with microcytic anemia. REV ASSOC MED BRAS. 2020;66(9):1277\u201382."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20912"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11571"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/20912"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-05-17T08:19:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-05-17T08:19:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4200"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"36113"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"ta